<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12045d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12045d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12045d"> 45(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Cit&eacute; des Livres / Culmen Contemplationis</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">17-18: La plus c&eacute;l&egrave;bre abbaye forteresse d&apos;un monde qui, au moyen &acirc;ge, m&eacute;rita d&apos;&ecirc;tre appel&eacute;e <mark>la Cit&eacute; des Livres</mark> a &eacute;t&eacute; l&apos;objet de travaux intellectuels d&apos;une valeur in&eacute;gale sans doute, mais en nombre consid&eacute;rable. Une des premi&egrave;res pages de son histoire a &eacute;t&eacute; &eacute;crite sur la toile grossi&egrave;re de la Broderie de Bayeux. C&apos;est le fragment o&ugrave; l&apos;on voit Harold et Guillaume, passant tous deux pr&egrave;s du sanctuaire de l&apos;Archange, avant d&apos;aller guerroyer contre Conan, duc de Bretagne<font color="green">[1]</font>. Le Mont appara&icirc;t, sur la toile de la reine Mathilde, massif et d&eacute;j&agrave; colossal avec ses arcades romanes. Ce n&apos;est d&eacute;j&agrave; plus le <i><mark>culmen contemplationis</mark></i> des anciennes chroniques, la forteresse s&apos;y devine. On sent que, plac&eacute; entre l&apos;enclume et le marteau, entre la Bretagne et la Normandie dont le duch&eacute; va s&apos;accro&icirc;tre d&apos;un royaume, il aura &agrave; subir d&apos;incessants assauts, &agrave; recevoir mais aussi &agrave; donner de rudes coups. <br><font color="green">[The most famous abbey-fortress of world which, in the middle ages, was rightfully called the City of Books, it has been the object of intellectual works of a considerable number but not always of the same value. One of the first pages of this history was written on the gross canvas of the Bayeux Tapestry. This is the fragment in which we see Harold and William, both of them passing the sanctuary of the Archangel, before warring against Conan, duke of Brittany. The Mont appears, on the canvas of queen Mathilda, massive and already colossal with Romanesque arcades. It is no longer the <i>culmen contemplationis</i> of the ancient chronicles, we can imagine the fortress. We feel that, caught between hammer and anvil, between Brittany and a Normandy where a duchy will grow into a kingdom, it will undergo countless attacks, receive but also give hard blows.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 17-18</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Dupont uses the term &lsquo;culmen contemplationis&rsquo; earlier in the book and explains that this is a hill that brings you closer to heaven. </mm> </dd></dl>
